While the simulations of Pritchett (2005, 2010) were based on persistent driving at the high-latitude boundaries, an alternative approach was taken by Hesse and Schindler (2001), Birn and Hesse (2014), and Y.-H. Liu et al. (2014b) using 2D PIC simulations. This approach was made, consistent with predictions from quasi-static, adiabatic equilibrium theory (Birn and Schindler 2002), on the basis that even moderate finite perturbations at the high-latitude boundaries could cause local thinning, current intensification and reduction of Bz\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
